definition.value: A single species phenotype which affects the pathogen's ability to penetrate a given experimental substance/membrane in an in vitro assay.

Penetration assays are often performed in vitro to assess pathogen penetration machinery. This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

A single species phenotype which affects the reproductive process. The production of new individuals that contain some portion of genetic material inherited from one or more parent organisms (GO:0000003).

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.
A single species population growth phenotype that affects the rate or extent of the increase in the number of unicellular organisms in the population (i.e organismal growth and reproduction).

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype that affects the binding of a gene product to another substance. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: abolished filamentous growth on host surface

definition.value: A pathogen colonization of host phenotype where the vegetative growth or proliferation of the pathogen on the host surface is abolished (it was present and is now absent).

label.value: absence of host-defense induced lesion by host hypersensitive response

definition.value: A phenotype where the process of host tissue cell death causing a host lesion is induced by the host activating its own hypersensitive response in defense, is absent.
This term is to be used for host protection against the pathogen. Note that if you are curating a necrotroph you need to annotate to PHIPO:0000465.

label.value: pathogen growth on host surface phenotype

definition.value: A pathogen colonization of host phenotype which affects the vegetative growth or proliferation of the pathogen on the host surface.

label.value: delayed host-defense induced lesion formation by host hypersensitive response

definition.value: A phenotype where the process of host tissue cell death causing a host lesion is induced by the host activating its own hypersensitive response in defense is delayed.
This term is to be used for host protection against the pathogen.

label.value: presence of host-defense induced lesion by host hypersensitive response

definition.value: A phenotype where the process of host tissue cell death causing a host lesion is induced by the host activating its own hypersensitive response in defense, is present.
This term is to be used for host protection against the pathogen. Note that if you are curating a necrotroph you need to annotate to PHIPO:0000477.
An individual organism growth phenotype in which the aerial height of hyphae is normal (indistinguishable from wild type).
Although this phenotype is for an individual it can be inferred from a population in a colony.

label.value: host chlorosis phenotype in presence of pathogen

definition.value: A pathogen-host interaction phenotype in which leaves produce insufficient chlorophyll.
An individual organism growth phenotype in which the aerial height of hyphae is decreased.
Although this phenotype is for an individual it can be inferred from a population in a colony.

A phenotype in which the balance of symbiotic mutualism has been disrupted compared to the normal interaction and the endosymbiont organism is able to show greater biomass within the host and/or the formation of visible disease formation symptoms compared to the normal interaction.
A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one pathogen protein to one host protein occurs to a lesser extent than normal.

label.value: host chlorosis absent in presence of pathogen

definition.value: A pathogen-host interaction phenotype in which host chlorosis is absent.
A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one pathogen protein to one host protein occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: host chlorosis present in presence of pathogen

definition.value: A pathogen-host interaction phenotype in which host chlorosis is present.

label.value: decreased level of pathogen deoxynivalenol within host

definition.value: A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the level of pathogen produced deoxynivalenol usually present during infection is lower than normal.

label.value: increased level of pathogen deoxynivalenol within host

definition.value: A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the level of pathogen produced deoxynivalenol usually present during infection is higher than normal.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the pathogen produced deoxynivalenol usually present during infection is present as normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the pathogen produced deoxynivalenol usually present during infection is absent or at a level too low to detect.
A single species phenotype that affects the localization of a structure or substance in a cell.

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.
A pathogen host interaction phenotype that affects the localization of a structure or substance in a cell.
Note that this term was reinstated from obsolete.

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.
A single organism phenotype that affects the localization of a protein in a cell.

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

A single organism phenotype in which the localization of a protein in a cell is abnormal. A protein may be observed in a place where it is not normally found, absent from a place where it is normally found, or both.

label.value: abnormal pathogen protein localization within host

definition.value: A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the localization of a pathogen protein in a host cell differs from normal.
A single organism phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein complex is abnormal.
A single organism phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is abnormal.

Encompasses both presence of proteins not normally found in the nucleus and decreased levels or absence of proteins normally found there, and describes defects in a localization process. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.
A single organism phenotype in which a protein does not localize to, and is therefore absent from, a place where it is normally found.
If this term is used, we recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay.

label.value: abolished pathogen protein localization within host

definition.value: A pathogen host interaction phenotype in which the localization of a pathogen protein to a host structure or compartment is abolished (i.e. the protein was localized to the host structure or compartment and now is not).
If this term is used, we recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay.

label.value: abolished pathogen protein localization to host nucleus

definition.value: A pathogen host interaction phenotype in which the localization of a pathogen protein to the host nucleus is abolished.
We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.
A single organism phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is abolished (GO:0034504).
We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.
A single organism phenotype that affects the localization of an RNA in a cell.

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

A single organism phenotype in which the localization of an RNA in a cell is abnormal. An RNA may be observed in a place where it is not normally found, absent from a place where it is normally found, or both.
A single organism phenotype in which the localization of an RNA in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A single organism cell phenotype that affects a transport process.

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.
A single organism phenotype in which a specific transport process is abnormal.
A single organism cellular process phenotype in which protein transport is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

A single organism cellular process phenotype in which endocytosis is abnormal. Endocytosis is a vesicle-mediated transport process in which cells take up external materials or membrane constituents by the invagination of a small region of the plasma membrane to form a new membrane-bounded vesicle. A phenotype may affect endocytosis of all cargoes, or of specific cargo such as a particular protein.
A single organism cellular process phenotype in which nuclear transport is abnormal.
A single organism cellular process phenotype in which protein transport is abnormal.
A single organism cellular process phenotype in which vacuolar transport is abnormal.
A single organism phenotype in which the localization of a protein in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal pathogen protein and host protein colocalization within host

definition.value: A pathogen host interaction phenotype, in which the colocalization of a pathogen protein and a host protein within a host cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A single organism phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type)(GO:0034504).

label.value: normal pathogen protein localization to host nucleus

definition.value: A pathogen host interaction phenotype in which the localization of a pathogen protein to the host nucleus is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A population phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of asexual spore germination is increased.
A phenotype that shows detectable differences from normal at the level of a tissue (eg leaf, inflorescence, ear or kidney).
A phenotype that does not show any detectable differences from normal at the level of a tissue (eg leaf, inflorescence, ear or kidney).

label.value: pathogen effector mediated modulation of host immune system process

definition.value: A phenotype dependent on an interaction between a pathogen effector and a host process in order for the pathogen to activate or suppress the host immune system. An effector is an entity derived from a pathogenic or non-pathogenic species that either activates or suppresses host defenses or other host responses.

To annotate a metagenotype containing a pathogen effector use 'GO:0140418 effector-mediated modulation of host process by symbiont' or a descendant. This is only to be used when there is manipulation of the host.
